2026-05-13 | Minimum Moves to Make Array Complementary

	Question
Return minimum moves needed.
	Key Insight
For one pair (a,b):
we analyze cost to make sum = S.
Possibilities:
- 0 moves:
		S = a+b  
- 1 move:
		S in [min(a,b)+1 , max(a,b)+limit]
- 2 moves:
		otherwise
Instead of checking every pair for every sum naively:
		use difference array.
	Approach
1.	For every pair:
		a = nums[i]
		b = nums[n-1-i]
2.	Update difference array for ranges:
		default cost = 2  
		1-move range decreases cost by 1  
		0-move point decreases cost by 1 more  
3.	Build prefix sums over all sums:
		possible sums from 2 → 2*limit
4.	Minimum value = answer.
	Time Complexity
	O(n + limit)
	Space Complexity
	O(limit)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    int minMoves(vector<int>& nums, int limit) {
        int n = nums.size();
        vector<int> diff(2 * limit + 2, 0);
        for(int i = 0; i < n / 2; i++){
            int a = nums[i];
            int b = nums[n - 1 - i];
            int low = min(a, b) + 1;
            int high = max(a, b) + limit;
            int sum = a + b;
            // initially 2 moves everywhere
            diff[2] += 2;
            // one move range
            diff[low] -= 1;
            diff[high + 1] += 1;
            // zero move at exact sum
            diff[sum] -= 1;
            diff[sum + 1] += 1;
            // restore after range
            diff[2 * limit + 1] -= 2;
        }
        int ans = INT_MAX;
        int curr = 0;
        for(int s = 2; s <= 2 * limit; s++){
            curr += diff[s];
            ans = min(ans, curr);
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
	Key Insight
Instead of evaluating each target sum separately:
		use range updates with difference array  
This converts:
		O(n × limit)
into:
		O(n + limit)  
A very important optimization technique for range-cost problems.
